{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488771"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:56:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:56:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"531"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"531","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/531"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.25,0.02,0.04,0.5]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"531"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83163"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"531","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/531"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"531"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68215"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1179"},{"type":"tags","id":"2210"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1055"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2359"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28475"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28480"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83163","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/83163"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 83-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a 24-hour history of increasing central abdominal pain. She had been well up until this episode of pain, which is constant in nature. Her medical history includes a colectomy for carcinoma ten years earlier, and she takes perindopril for hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, a midline swelling is evident beneath the laparotomy scar and is tender to touch, with the overlying skin reddened. The swelling \u0027gurgles\u0027 on palpation and cannot be reduced.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStandard laboratory blood investigations are performed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ultrasound examination of the swelling","CT abdomen","Fine needle aspiration","Intravenous fluids and gut rest","Laparotomy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a strangulated incisional hernia. The swelling can be diagnosed clinically as an incisional hernia based on its position immediately under the abdominal surgical scar and that air can be compressed within the lumen on palpation. The finding of localised tenderness indicates that the hernia has strangulated. The term \u0027strangulation\u0027 means that there is an ischaemic element to the pathological process and that all or part of the contents of the hernial sac are in danger of necrosis. Therefore, the only realistic management option is surgical intervention and a \u003Cstrong\u003Elaparotomy\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound examination of the swelling\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary in this case because the clinical findings are sufficient to diagnose a strangulated hernia, and imaging would not change the immediate need for surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT abdomen\u003C/strong\u003E might be used in some cases to confirm the diagnosis of a hernia or assess its contents, but in this scenario, the clinical presentation is clear enough to proceed directly to surgery without delay.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFine needle aspiration\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate for a hernia, as it is not a fluid-filled lesion that requires aspiration, and this procedure would not address the underlying issue of strangulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous fluids and gut rest\u003C/strong\u003E are supportive measures that might be used in conjunction with other treatments, but they do not address the urgent need for surgical intervention in a strangulated hernia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute abdominal pain and associated localised tenderness means peritonitis - and surgical intervention will usually be indicated.","Strangulated hernias require urgent surgical intervention to prevent necrosis of the entrapped bowel.","Clinical examination can often provide sufficient information to diagnose a strangulated hernia, making immediate surgical intervention necessary."],"references":["Walming S, Angenete E, Block M, Bock D, Gessler B, Haglind E. Retrospective review of risk factors for surgical wound dehiscence and incisional hernia. BMC Surg. 2017 Feb 22;17(1):19. doi: 10.1186/s12893-017-0207-0. PMID: 28222776; PMCID: PMC5320761. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28222776/","Xing L, Culbertson EJ, Wen Y, Franz MG. Early laparotomy wound failure as the mechanism for incisional hernia formation. J Surg Res. 2013 Jun 1;182(1):e35-42. doi: 10.1016/j.jss.2012.09.009. Epub 2012 Sep 23. PMID: 23036516; PMCID: PMC4492695. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4492695/","Pastorino A, Alshuqayfi AA. Strangulated Hernia. [Updated 2022 Dec 19]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK555972/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68215"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"531"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68215","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68215"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-02T11:22:27+10:30